🦖 What This Show Meant to Me
A personal reflection by Greyson — Founder of DinoStudios

When I think about my childhood, there aren’t a lot of big, loud, famous shows that define it.
No FGTEEV.
No LankyBox.
No giant YouTube channels everyone else watched.

My childhood was carried by something quieter, something smaller, something almost secret — a Minecraft dinosaur series on Tankee called Dinos Reborn.

I didn’t know it at the time, but that show became the center of my imagination.
It wasn’t just entertainment.
It was comfort.
It was adventure.
It was the thing my brain reached for when I was bored, sad, lonely, or just needed something familiar.

I was a dinosaur kid from the moment I watched Jurassic Park at age 3 or 4.
Dinosaurs weren’t just creatures to me — they were characters, friends, entire worlds.
So when I found a Minecraft series with:

Milo the Dryosaurus

Felicity the Spinosaurus

George the Gallimimus

a jeep

a barn

DNA machines

a sunset biome

a host guiding the adventure

…it felt like the show had been made for me.

I didn’t watch anything else on Tankee.
Just this.
Over and over.
It became my comfort show, my safe place, my favorite world to escape into.

And then one day, it was gone.

No clips.
No screenshots.
No episode list.
No mentions online.
No proof it ever existed.

All I had left were memories — tiny pieces of a world I thought I’d never see again.

But those memories stayed.
They stayed for years.
They stayed so strongly that I eventually went searching for the show again.

And somehow…
I found it.

Not just a clip.
Not just a thumbnail.
The entire series, fully intact, on Tankee and HappyKids TV.

I didn’t just rediscover a show.
I rediscovered a piece of myself.

I remembered why I loved dinosaurs.
I remembered why Minecraft felt magical.
I remembered the feeling of being a kid again, watching Milo and Felicity and George like they were real.

This show didn’t just entertain me.
It shaped me.
It carried my childhood.
And now, thanks to this investigation, it’s finally found — not just online, but in my life again.

This reflection is here to remind me that sometimes the things we think are lost forever aren’t gone.
They’re just waiting for us to come back.

And I did.

— Greyson
DinoStudios Founder
Case Closed
